    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix lte_gold_new() bit assembly in DMRS sequence generation\n\n### Summary\nThe `lte_gold_new()` function in the NR DMRS sequence generation code contains a critical bug in the verification logic that causes incorrect bit assembly when comparing optimized and reference Gold sequence implementations. This leads to false verification failures and potential undefined behavior during NR cell initialization.\n\nWhen the `CHECK_GOLD_SEQUENCE` compile flag is enabled, the function attempts to reconstruct 32-bit words from individual bits generated by `pseudo_random_sequence()`. However, the bit positioning logic incorrectly uses `<<j` instead of `<<(j-k)`, where `k` is the starting bit index for the current 32-bit word. This causes bits to be placed at incorrect positions when `j >= 32`, leading to corrupted verification data.\n\nAdditionally, there's no bounds checking to prevent reading beyond the allocated `dmrs_sequence` buffer, which can cause memory access violations.\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Compile OAI5G with `CHECK_GOLD_SEQUENCE` flag enabled\n2. Initialize NR gNB with any valid NID_cell value\n3. Call `lte_gold_new()` during DMRS table initialization\n4. Observe assertion failure in bit comparison logic or potential segfault\n\n### Symptoms\n- Assertion failure: \"Error in gold sequence computation for ns X l Y and index Z\"\n- Segmentation fault when `CELL_DMRS_LENGTH` is exceeded\n- Incorrect DMRS sequence generation affecting PBCH decoding\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/NR_REFSIG/dmrs_nr.c`: Fixed bit assembly logic in `lte_gold_new()` function to correctly position bits within 32-bit words using `(j-k)` shift instead of `j`\n- `openair1/PHY/NR_REFSIG/dmrs_nr.c`: Added bounds checking to prevent buffer overflows when accessing `dmrs_sequence` array\n"
}